<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-058-510  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 058 510.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  March 1989 v7 n3 p21(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The data in everything. (Data bases in related applications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Landry, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Applications developers are integrating data bases far outside ofthe typical data base management systems.andP;  Word processors,utility packages and other applications integrate a data base ofinformation within their code.andP;  The ultimate goal is to have asingle data base power a variety of applications, all using thesame interface and the same command structure.andP;  The idea is toenforce user loyalty to a manufacturer.andP;  By becoming comfortablewith an interface, the user supposedly buys other products fromthe same manufacturer.andP;  However, the theory does not always workin practice.andP;  Few users have need for the variety of products froma single manufacturer.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data BasesProduct DevelopmentIntegrated ApproachApplicationsPerformance MeasurementUser NeedsMarketing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>